      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "The cartoon sounds natural: make a charged sphere spin, and it carries angular momentum plus a magnetic moment. But now make the cartoon pay its numerical bill.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "rotate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.83,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:04:20"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Give the imagined ball the classical electron radius, about two point eight two femtometers. This is a classical electromagnetic length scale, not a measured material surface.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "measure"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.82,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:04:20"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Treat it as a uniform solid sphere. Even ask it to reproduce only h bar over two, the size of one measured spin projection—a deliberately generous target.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.11,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:04:20"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "For that classical model, angular momentum equals moment of inertia times angular speed, and rim speed equals angular speed times radius.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "trace"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.87,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:04:20"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Insert the electron mass, the assumed radius, and h bar. The required equatorial speed comes out near five point one times ten to the ten meters per second.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.73,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:04:20"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Divide by the speed of light: roughly one hundred seventy. The gauge does not merely cross c; it destroys the scale.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "rotate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.13,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:04:20"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Special relativity forbids material at the rim from outrunning light. So the literal rotating-sphere model contradicts the rules it must obey.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "impact"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.66,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:04:20"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Could a smaller sphere rescue it? No. In this model the required rim speed grows as one over radius. Shrinking the ball makes the failure worse.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "transform"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.55,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:04:20"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Electron spin is nevertheless real angular momentum. It has quantized projections, contributes to magnetic effects, and combines with other angular momenta by precise quantum rules.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.48,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:04:20"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The word spin survived; the mechanical picture did not. Spin is intrinsic—a built-in quantum property like mass or charge, not stuff circulating through space.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
